<div id="review_1428842301" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1428842301" />
    <a title="Lynne King" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15736557-lynne-king"><img alt="Lynne King" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1357126217p2/15736557.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1428842301?book_show_action=true">Oct 30, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lynne King" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lynne King" href="/user/show/15736557-lynne-king">Lynne King</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15736557-lynne-king?shelf=a-must-to-read">a-must-to-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15736557-lynne-king?shelf=2016-books-to-be-read">2016-books-to-be-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1428842301" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4162462257010905246">I hate to say this as it sounds so trite and I’m certainly not religious but this is indeed one of those novels that has been touched by the hand of grace. Marilynne Robinson in her unique inimitable way has produced a sublime work that exquisitely captures the life of Reverend Boughton and his children Glory and Jack. This novel encapsulates the ideals of family life and solidarity regardless of what becomes of them and what is so touching is that Jack, the wayward son, who did everything out o</span>
  <span id="freeText4162462257010905246" style="display:none">I hate to say this as it sounds so trite and I’m certainly not religious but this is indeed one of those novels that has been touched by the hand of grace. Marilynne Robinson in her unique inimitable way has produced a sublime work that exquisitely captures the life of Reverend Boughton and his children Glory and Jack. This novel encapsulates the ideals of family life and solidarity regardless of what becomes of them and what is so touching is that Jack, the wayward son, who did everything out of sync, be it theft, drunkenness, etc. still retained the love of his father and even greater than Jack’s other siblings. The book actually quite overwhelmed me in this sense of forgiveness and yet of love in Reverend Boughton’s waiting and waiting for his wayward son, his doubts and misgivings and finally when Jack returns, well it was worth it.<br /><br />As Reverend Boughton’s life draws to a close, his long suffering daughter Glory is close by his side, easing him through this troubled time but his lifeline is Jack, his mercurial child but still so loved.<br /><br />This is not a fast moving book but one to be deliciously savoured as a good Medoc. Hidden aspects are constantly uncovered and the lyrical writing of Robinson, especially her descriptions, adds such beauty that will not be seen again for a long time. <br /><br />There’s such a spirit of place about this book. Glory, who had loved her brother as a child, now finds him difficult but slowly they develop a mutual love and it is rather splendid to see.<br /><br />I consider Jack comparable to the elusive kingfisher with its fleeting appearance above the river bank, the flash of electric blue that brings that magical aspect, be it somewhat ephemeral to a human somehow but it nevertheless manages to project the soul of Jack, despite his misdemeanors into a powerful personality not to be reckoned with.<br /><br />It’s also interesting to see how Jack’s relationship with Reverend Boughton’s closest friend, the Reverend John Ames develops. Plus the latter’s rather unique wife Laila, a former itinerant and now fully ensconced into the church and yet, despite her happy contented life, she remains unsettled. She views her much loved elderly husband and knows that she will see his burial and then, perhaps the bird of paradise will escape from her gilded cage that has so suited her for the moment. She doesn’t know. It is delightful to see John Ames face as he observes his wife. It is as though he will never know what she will project and he continues to be entranced by her...Touching.<br /><br />A remarkable and sobering book. Much loved by me and to be reread many times.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4162462257010905246" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

