    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2519118523" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2519118523" />
    <a title="HBalikov" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/929238-hbalikov"><img alt="HBalikov" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1271764879p2/929238.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2519118523?book_show_action=true">Sep 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="HBalikov" class="user" itemprop="url" name="HBalikov" href="/user/show/929238-hbalikov">HBalikov</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8216909-home">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2519118523" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14293722764483835682">What is a “home?” Can you ever go “home?” I am a bit confounded by my attempts to write a review of this novel.<br/><br/>When Benjamin Franklin said “A house is not a home….” he was concerned with a place that provided “food and fire for the mind as well as the body.” I am not sure how Marilynne Robinson would make the distinction between the two but she gives us many clues.<br/><br/>&quot;Twenty years was long enough to make a stranger of someone she had known far better than this brother of hers, and here he was in he</span>
  <span id="freeText14293722764483835682" style="display:none">What is a “home?” Can you ever go “home?” I am a bit confounded by my attempts to write a review of this novel.<br /><br />When Benjamin Franklin said “A house is not a home….” he was concerned with a place that provided “food and fire for the mind as well as the body.” I am not sure how Marilynne Robinson would make the distinction between the two but she gives us many clues.<br /><br />"Twenty years was long enough to make a stranger of someone she had known far better than this brother of hers, and here he was in her kitchen, pale and ill at ease and in no state to receive the kindness prepared for him, awaiting him, even then wilting and congealing into the worst he could have meant by the word “lunch.” And what an ugly word that was anyway."<br /><br />"Did she choose to be there, in that house, in Gilead? No, she certainly did not. Her father needed looking after, and she had to be somewhere, like every other human being on earth. What an embarrassment that was, being somewhere because there was nowhere else for you to be. All those years of work and nothing to show for it. But you make the best of things."<br /><br />Home explores the dynamics of the Boughton family in rural Iowa during the 1950s. All the children have grown up and left the house they were raised in. Their mother has died. Their father, a minister now retired, is “getting on” and needs some help to get downstairs for meals (he can’t prepare on his own) and upstairs to bathe and sleep. His daughter, Glory, is persuaded to come back (she has no husband or children) and be the caregiver. <br /><br />Eventually, she is joined (soon after this book begins) by her “prodigal” brother, Jack. When they were growing up Jack was both a truant and thief. He says that he felt he never fit in and that the house they lived in was not a home for him. Glory feels her obligations to the family but also feels “trapped.”<br /><br />The boys all had conventional names such as John or Theodore while the girls were named Faith, Hope, Grace and Glory. There certainly seems to be an imbalance in the expectations of the parents had of their children. Some of that was by gender. Other parts of that expectation were determined by behavior. Glory gave in to the expectation that, since she was the only one of the sibling women who was not married, she should be the one to come back and take care of her father.<br /><br />As the story unfolds the characters begin to reveal or share the secrets that have colored the choices they made and their assumptions about each other. Most of this takes place in one of the downstairs rooms of the Boughton house or on the porch or in the garden or barn. An underlying theme is how much each person wishes things to be different or the same and what they will do to assure that outcome. The book could easily be rewritten as a drama for the stage.<br /><br />The characters are well-drawn. The story is rich with drama. Perhaps, if I had read Gilead, Robinson’s first book about this corner of Iowa, I would feel that I understood more about these people and my empathy would have been greater. Most of the story is told from Glory’s perspective and because of that the reader is encouraged to identify with her. I guess in the 1950s it might have been that a daughter with “limited prospects” would be expected to come home and become caregiver. (Given that, it is also not a surprise that her father wanted her name to be Charity.) Yet, I kept waiting for her to express more of what she really wanted to do either at the moment of the story or after her father’s eventual death.<br /><br />My spouse I believe would give Home that 5th star and I can’t fault her for doing so.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14293722764483835682" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


