  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_217447430" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/217447430" />
    <a title="Laysee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4863523-laysee"><img alt="Laysee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459741824p2/4863523.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/217447430?book_show_action=true">Sep 30, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laysee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laysee" href="/user/show/4863523-laysee">Laysee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781429929042" href="/book/show/6985516-home">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer217447430" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16331153180721291587">“Home” is set in Gilead, Iowa, of the sunflowers. It tells the story of “greying children” taking care of their “ancient father”. Glory, aged 38, the youngest of 6 children, returned home to live with her father, the Reverend Robert Boughton, after her marriage fell apart. Her brother, Jack, who had a reputation of being a scoundrel also returned home from his wandering and bitterness after 20 years. Both were unprepared to encounter a father so sad and old. Robinson wrote with empathic apprecia</span>
  <span id="freeText16331153180721291587" style="display:none">“Home” is set in Gilead, Iowa, of the sunflowers. It tells the story of “greying children” taking care of their “ancient father”. Glory, aged 38, the youngest of 6 children, returned home to live with her father, the Reverend Robert Boughton, after her marriage fell apart. Her brother, Jack, who had a reputation of being a scoundrel also returned home from his wandering and bitterness after 20 years. Both were unprepared to encounter a father so sad and old. Robinson wrote with empathic appreciation of the struggles familiar to individuals coming to terms with the infirmities of aging, the pain of care giving, and the heartache of loving people closest to oneself. One of the questions that emerged for me as I read this novel was: Why does caring for someone hurt so much? Robinson astutely captured the pathos and irony of home – “What kinder place could there be on earth, and why did it seem to them all like exile?” Indeed, “Home” poses a few hard questions. For Jack, the question is: How does a person live out the rest of one's life when one has done something terrible and it cannot be undone? There are no answers to such questions.<br /><br />“Home” is a novel one should read after “Gilead”. In Gilead, Jack Boughton was perceived from the perspective of the Reverend Ames as an incorrigible trouble maker whom he feared would corrupt his wife and young son. In Home, Robinson afforded a fresh set of lenses that allowed us to see Jack in a different light. It’s all about perspective. Despite the roguishness we’ve come to expect of Jack, we now see him unlacing his father's shoes and carrying him to bed. We also see him struggling to come home to himself, a bone-weary man conscious of negative public opinion, trying desperately to redeem himself in his father's eyes. It is also extremely disquieting that a child like Jack brought up in a seemingly God-fearing family could be made to feel like a misfit even though he was his father’s most beloved child. By the time the novel ends, you cannot help but feel sorry for Jack and even grow to like him and wish he would have another chance to turn his life around.<br /><br />I guess “Home” is likely to affect the reader deeply in different ways depending on his or her experiences and where s/he is along the continuum of living and dying. That said, there is the unmistakable, underlying thread of communion of being human, finding forgiveness, and learning to be thankful for the little blessings of an imperfect life. Robinson said it well, "There is so much to be grateful for, words are poor things." <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16331153180721291587" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

