  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1670724910" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1670724910" />
    <a title="J.C." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52123967-j-c"><img alt="J.C." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610295104p2/52123967.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1670724910?book_show_action=true">Jun 16, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.C." class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.C." href="/user/show/52123967-j-c">J.C.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52123967-j-c?shelf=american">american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1670724910" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15157095143002963965">I&apos;ve just re-read “Home” after having been given Marilynne Robinson&apos;s latest book, &quot;Jack&quot;, which is concerned with the years before Jack, the beloved prodigal son, returns home. &quot;Home&quot; is the second book in the Gilead set. He’s not the only one to have returned; his sister, Glory, has come back to look after their father, a Presbyterian minister who is now old and frail. She has her own troubled past, which she has kept hidden. Much of the book is a slow, intimate, building of the relationship b</span>
  <span id="freeText15157095143002963965" style="display:none">I've just re-read “Home” after having been given Marilynne Robinson's latest book, "Jack", which is concerned with the years before Jack, the beloved prodigal son, returns home. "Home" is the second book in the Gilead set. He’s not the only one to have returned; his sister, Glory, has come back to look after their father, a Presbyterian minister who is now old and frail. She has her own troubled past, which she has kept hidden. Much of the book is a slow, intimate, building of the relationship between Jack and the sister who was a young teenager when he left home, but who helped deal with a tragedy he left behind. There’s no swift unburdening of souls; the intensity of emotion and the attempts at becoming reconciled to one’s past are drawn from the details of life in the old house, the sense of being enchanted, or trapped, by the expectations of the past, the life one has lived, and the gentle, insistent voice of faith in the old minister and in his friend, John Ames, the Congregationalist minister whom we met in “Gilead”. No easy solutions are presented by this offered faith, and the deepest questions remain unanswered in any rational sense, but grace is always present. It pervades anything that this author creates. I loved “Gilead”, but every book I have read by this author seems to take strides further into these people she has created, and “Home” has lead me straight on to re-read the next in the series, “Lila”, which I’ll review in a few days (if I haven’t already done so!). But as I read each of them they seem more powerful than the last!<br />When I finished re-reading “Home” my first impulse was whether or not to proceed with an idea I had had, to give a copy of “Gilead” to a friend of mine who is deeply religious and who belongs to a strict church. “Gilead” is the most straightforward of the books and the central character is John Ames, a minister. I should have pointed out in my really brief review of “Gilead” that there is a fantastic figure in “Gilead” of John Ames’ grandfather, also a minister, but one who took up arms in the Civil War). I feel sure my friend would appreciate this first book in the set; but I had the strange notion that if she went on to read the other books I didn’t want Jack judged by the standards of religion as it is often observed in our society. In that way I am of course imposing my own judgement. Jack, alcoholic, thief, and ‘bum’, is a precious soul, a refinement of suffering and integrity far from the sensibilities that most of us can attain as we go about our daily lives. <br />“Home” is so very sad, and so sensitively written – Marilynne Robinson has a wonderful gift for tense dialogue, and the minutest interaction between people. She said (in a recent “Start the Week” programme on BBC Radio 4) that religion in America just now does not encourage a positive, hopeful and respectful attitude to others. These books do.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15157095143002963965" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1670724910">
