<div id="review_1877756127" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1877756127" />
    <a title="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35482263-gumble-s-yard---golden-reviewer"><img alt="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607273231p2/35482263.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1877756127?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" href="/user/show/35482263-gumble-s-yard---golden-reviewer">Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35482263-gumble-s-yard---golden-reviewer?shelf=2015">2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35482263-gumble-s-yard---golden-reviewer?shelf=women-prize-winners">women-prize-winners</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1877756127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17564316331640969647">A companion novel to “Gilead” told in the third person and telling the story of Jack Broughton, his father Rev Broughton and particularly his youngest sister – Glory, living back at home after her fiancée of many years finally stopped his deceit of her (admitting he was married). Many of the scenes directly overlap with “Home” but are viewed by other observers – particularly the interactions between Jack and Ames (mainly recounted by Jack to Glory).<br/><br/>As brilliantly written as “Gilead” although wit</span>
  <span id="freeText17564316331640969647" style="display:none">A companion novel to “Gilead” told in the third person and telling the story of Jack Broughton, his father Rev Broughton and particularly his youngest sister – Glory, living back at home after her fiancée of many years finally stopped his deceit of her (admitting he was married). Many of the scenes directly overlap with “Home” but are viewed by other observers – particularly the interactions between Jack and Ames (mainly recounted by Jack to Glory).<br /><br />As brilliantly written as “Gilead” although with a very different note – this is a portrayal of disappointment, of hope prolonged and ultimately disappointed, of the difficult of forgiveness and of being forgiven and of forgiving oneself, of the difficult of being a non-repentant but regretful prodigal, of grace and its limitations at least in human form, of both disappointed and unformed faith, of loneliness and isolation especially in a crowd and a family, of ageing (both old age and lapsing into a middle age that didn’t match ones dreams or hopes), of redemption and pre-destination<br /><br />Ultimately a hugely moving and deeply sad novel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17564316331640969647" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


