    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1609635251" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1609635251" />
    <a title="Sohaib" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31777090-sohaib"><img alt="Sohaib" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616598903p2/31777090.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1609635251?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sohaib" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sohaib" href="/user/show/31777090-sohaib">Sohaib</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781844085507" href="/book/show/6097133-home">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31777090-sohaib?shelf=2016-reads">2016-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31777090-sohaib?shelf=literature">literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1609635251" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4843685615765277708">A wonderful read! <i>Home</i> is about family, love, life and second chances. I really enjoyed Glory’s account of what happens throughout the novel, although at one point I was tempted to question the reality of what she thinks or wonder about how other characters perceive the same incidents. Her narrative, however, is remarkable, cautious and meticulous when it comes to her brother and father, adding to the familial intensity (this is called a third person limited narrator if you are wondering and I g</span>
  <span id="freeText4843685615765277708" style="display:none">A wonderful read! <i>Home</i> is about family, love, life and second chances. I really enjoyed Glory’s account of what happens throughout the novel, although at one point I was tempted to question the reality of what she thinks or wonder about how other characters perceive the same incidents. Her narrative, however, is remarkable, cautious and meticulous when it comes to her brother and father, adding to the familial intensity (this is called a third person limited narrator if you are wondering and I guess Robinson intentionally wrote it this way to fit this book dialogically into the trilogy). I only read <i>Housekeeping</i> for Robinson by the way.<br><br>The overarching theme in <i>Home</i> is God’s Providence and how our conscious perception is always hindered by what we do not know or cannot understand. Our judgments and perception of others are often skewed because of our unconscious attachment to our subjective experiences and what we do not know. After all, we can only have our own experience to give, measure and judge other people and experiences upon. It would be interesting to read <i>Lila</i> and <i>Gilead</i>; to complete the trilogy and the characters view on things – to completely understand the dialogicity of the three novels.<br><br>Putting <i>Housekeeping</i> and <i>Home</i> side by side, the two are postmodern narratives, optimistic and vivacious. <i>Housekeeping</i> focuses on the initiation phase and getting the journey going, the journey of transience for Ruth and Sylvie. <i>Home</i> focuses on the return phase, the phase where all the doing is done, where the journey is about to end and the characters have been through all the battles and have the scars to show for it now (think why Jack’s scar under his eye keeps popping up in the novel). It is interesting how Robinson shifts the traditional focus of most narratives, given that we view every novel in the journey motif frame. <i>Home</i> foregrounds what happens (or what does not happen) in the most inactive phase, the return phase. Jack’s transformation has already happened after he returns back home, but all the tension ensues because of the characters’ failure to understand this (even Jack himself) …<br><br>All in all, <i>Home</i> is a wonderful read! Can’t wait to get my hands on <i>Gilead</i> and <i>Lila</i>, especially <i>Lila</i> because of the narrator’s transient background, which is reminiscent of a some kind of sequel for <i>Housekeeping</i>’s Ruth and Sylvie.<br><br><a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img alt="Creative Commons License" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1406704146i/10586746.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>This review is licensed under a <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4843685615765277708" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


