    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1091220374" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1091220374" />
    <a title="Stephen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8201780-stephen"><img alt="Stephen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1412473145p2/8201780.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1091220374?book_show_action=true">Oct 28, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen" href="/user/show/8201780-stephen">Stephen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1091220374" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12038607143168179438">I don&apos;t get the rave reviews for this novel nor why it won the Orange Prize. Feels like a case of rewarding reputation versus substance. Found it hard to get into because of the very formal, stilted writing that opens the book. Picks up when the dialogue kicks in; drags as the same conversations are repeated over and over. Ultimately goes no where. For a book supposedly about redemption, NO ONE in <i>Home</i> is redeemed. In fact, no one develops at all. Glory is lost with no where to go when she arriv</span>
  <span id="freeText12038607143168179438" style="display:none">I don't get the rave reviews for this novel nor why it won the Orange Prize. Feels like a case of rewarding reputation versus substance. Found it hard to get into because of the very formal, stilted writing that opens the book. Picks up when the dialogue kicks in; drags as the same conversations are repeated over and over. Ultimately goes no where. For a book supposedly about redemption, NO ONE in <i>Home</i> is redeemed. In fact, no one develops at all. Glory is lost with no where to go when she arrives in Gilead and lost with no where else to go when the book ends. Jack is a despondent loser when he arrives and the same when he leaves. Their father is a pious worrier from beginning to end. Ames neither forgets nor is forgives. In total, 325 pages of people not where they want to be but incapable to moving on. On my buy, borrow or skip scale, <i>Home</i> is a borrow at best.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12038607143168179438" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

